1
00:00:17,250 --> 00:00:18,416
[COOPER]
As of right now,

2
00:00:18,500 --> 00:00:20,583
we haven't managed to
track down Zabel yet.

3
00:00:20,666 --> 00:00:22,958
But, the latest case
made one thing quite clear.

4
00:00:23,041 --> 00:00:25,000
If we're ever going to take
down Esperanza for good,

5
00:00:25,083 --> 00:00:27,791
we have no choice but
to combine our forces.

6
00:00:27,875 --> 00:00:29,458
SEVEN-O and the military?

7
00:00:29,541 --> 00:00:31,750
Yes, I must admit, I was
incredibly impressed

8
00:00:31,833 --> 00:00:33,166
during the fake kidnapping.

9
00:00:33,250 --> 00:00:34,708
Particularly with
the young detective

10
00:00:34,791 --> 00:00:36,583
who rescued his partner.

11
00:00:37,958 --> 00:00:40,750
[DOUG] It's the perfect day
for hang-drying laundry.

12
00:00:40,833 --> 00:00:42,875
You're obsessed
with mundane crap!

13
00:00:42,958 --> 00:00:44,333
Huh?

14
00:00:44,416 --> 00:00:45,916
You damn well better have
written your report by now!

15
00:00:46,000 --> 00:00:47,291
My writing hand still--

16
00:00:47,375 --> 00:00:48,666
I don't care--we're not
allowed back on the streets

17
00:00:48,750 --> 00:00:50,083
until you turn it in!

18
00:00:51,083 --> 00:00:53,333
Hey, pretty girl, how much?

19
00:00:53,416 --> 00:00:54,875
What'll this buy?

20
00:02:26,375 --> 00:02:27,666
[GUS]
If I'd known you were a cop,

21
00:02:27,750 --> 00:02:29,375
I never would've approached you.

22
00:02:29,458 --> 00:02:30,875
You think that makes it okay?

23
00:02:30,958 --> 00:02:33,333
Well, I didn't realize you
were a pretty dude, either!

24
00:02:33,416 --> 00:02:35,333
Epic fail all around.

25
00:02:35,416 --> 00:02:37,666
You wanna talk about this
down at the station?!

26
00:02:37,750 --> 00:02:38,875
[growls]

27
00:02:38,958 --> 00:02:41,083
[DOUG] Stop. Just let
him have a warning.

28
00:02:41,166 --> 00:02:42,541
But this punk clearly
intended to--

29
00:02:42,625 --> 00:02:45,125
You don't just look like a girl,
you act like one, too.

30
00:02:45,208 --> 00:02:47,250
--Yeah?! So, what?!
--[DOUG laughing]

31
00:02:47,333 --> 00:02:48,958
There you are...

32
00:02:49,041 --> 00:02:51,791
Sorry. I hope he wasn't
causing you any trouble.

33
00:02:51,875 --> 00:02:53,333
--[KIRILL] Oh, no.
--[GUS] Come on, Pops.

34
00:02:53,416 --> 00:02:55,041
You need to get back in bed.

35
00:02:55,125 --> 00:02:57,875
[JEFFREY] Well, I got worried
and had to find you.

36
00:02:57,958 --> 00:02:59,291
Am I free to go?

37
00:02:59,375 --> 00:03:01,000
Uh. Yeah.

38
00:03:01,083 --> 00:03:02,500
[GUS]
You're so sweaty.

39
00:03:02,583 --> 00:03:03,833
'Scuse me, Nurse?!

40
00:03:03,916 --> 00:03:05,750
Can you bring us
a wheelchair, please?

41
00:03:05,833 --> 00:03:07,750
Son, I can walk back on my own.

42
00:03:07,833 --> 00:03:10,666
Don't force yourself.
You're too weak!

43
00:03:10,750 --> 00:03:14,708
Well, I guess he's not that bad
of a kid after all, right?

44
00:03:14,791 --> 00:03:16,958
Huh?! Asshole!

45
00:03:17,416 --> 00:03:19,583
[NARRATOR]
Of course, Doug is fully aware

46
00:03:19,666 --> 00:03:22,250
that his partner's not allowed
back on the streets until he

47
00:03:22,333 --> 00:03:26,125
fills out all his paperwork
from their previous case.

48
00:03:27,791 --> 00:03:29,125
[NARRATOR]
But, Doug?

49
00:03:29,208 --> 00:03:31,916
He wants some time off,
and he's damn well gettin' it!

50
00:03:32,000 --> 00:03:34,375
He's in for an earful
as soon as I find him!

51
00:03:34,458 --> 00:03:36,541
[DEANA]
You little piece of shit!

52
00:03:36,625 --> 00:03:38,875
First of all, I ain't a hooker,
second, that's illegal,

53
00:03:38,958 --> 00:03:41,250
and third, you think this
chump change'd be enough?

54
00:03:41,333 --> 00:03:43,291
Look, ma'am, I wasn't
even asking you.

55
00:03:43,375 --> 00:03:45,958
I was interested in a night
with your little sister.

56
00:03:46,041 --> 00:03:48,125
I'll let that slide,
since you're a kid.

57
00:03:48,208 --> 00:03:50,291
You're way too young
to appreciate the beauty...

58
00:03:50,375 --> 00:03:52,666
Deana, calm down!
Control yourself!

59
00:03:52,750 --> 00:03:54,625
Guess this twerp hasn't
learned his lesson yet.

60
00:03:54,708 --> 00:03:55,583
[KAY]
Oh! Kirill!

61
00:03:55,666 --> 00:03:57,041
What the--?

62
00:03:57,125 --> 00:03:58,958
I guess losers of a feather
really do flock together.

63
00:03:59,041 --> 00:03:59,875
[DEANA growls]

64
00:03:59,958 --> 00:04:00,791
[KAY]
Deana! Stop!

65
00:04:00,875 --> 00:04:02,333
[GUS grunts, laughs]

66
00:04:02,416 --> 00:04:04,875
I don't know what it is, but
that kid really pisses me off.

67
00:04:04,958 --> 00:04:06,083
Yeah. Me, too.

68
00:04:06,166 --> 00:04:07,291
Hate to tell ya,

69
00:04:07,375 --> 00:04:09,333
especially since you
made the trip down here,

70
00:04:09,416 --> 00:04:11,083
but I've been chasing Doug
around the hospital

71
00:04:11,166 --> 00:04:12,083
all damn day.

72
00:04:12,166 --> 00:04:13,958
Well, we didn't
come to see Doug.

73
00:04:14,041 --> 00:04:16,416
--[KIRILL] Huh?
--We're here on a case.

74
00:04:16,500 --> 00:04:18,250
[KAY]
We've brought photographs.

75
00:04:18,333 --> 00:04:20,958
They're of four people who've
died under strange circumstances

76
00:04:21,041 --> 00:04:24,166
in the past few months.

77
00:04:24,250 --> 00:04:27,000
Our investigation revealed that
all four of the deceased men

78
00:04:27,083 --> 00:04:29,833
had a couple of things
in common. First of all,

79
00:04:29,916 --> 00:04:32,791
every single one of them
was a confirmed Anthem user.

80
00:04:32,875 --> 00:04:34,166
And the other commonality...

81
00:04:34,250 --> 00:04:35,791
...is that they were
all former patients

82
00:04:35,875 --> 00:04:37,583
of this hospital, right?

83
00:04:37,666 --> 00:04:39,041
Wow.

84
00:04:39,125 --> 00:04:41,291
Here you are,
running this entire joint,

85
00:04:41,375 --> 00:04:42,958
yet you've still got
enough time to learn

86
00:04:43,041 --> 00:04:44,541
the names and faces of
all the patients?

87
00:04:44,625 --> 00:04:47,541
You're speaking to the leading
authority in end-of-life care.

88
00:04:47,625 --> 00:04:51,000
This doctor... He does
everything he can--

89
00:04:51,083 --> 00:04:54,250
Each of these men was informed
they didn't have long to live.

90
00:04:54,333 --> 00:04:56,416
We were developing a care
plan for all of them.

91
00:04:56,500 --> 00:04:58,333
But, before anything
was finalized,

92
00:04:58,416 --> 00:05:00,125
they forced their way
out of the hospital.

93
00:05:00,208 --> 00:05:03,333
I can understand why they'd
turn to Anthem as an escape.

94
00:05:03,416 --> 00:05:04,791
They were desperate for relief.

95
00:05:04,875 --> 00:05:07,416
If I didn't know better,
I'd call that an endorsement.

96
00:05:07,500 --> 00:05:09,125
We endorse drugs all the time.

97
00:05:09,208 --> 00:05:09,958
[DEANA]
Huh...?

98
00:05:10,041 --> 00:05:11,208
Medicine or poison?

99
00:05:11,291 --> 00:05:12,375
It's a fine line.

100
00:05:12,458 --> 00:05:14,583
It comes down to
how the drug is used.

101
00:05:14,666 --> 00:05:17,416
I wonder... Do you even
understand how Anthem

102
00:05:17,500 --> 00:05:19,708
affects the human body
and its various processes?

103
00:05:19,791 --> 00:05:21,875
[BOTH gasp]

104
00:05:21,958 --> 00:05:23,625
[KIRILL] There's this
gene editing technology

105
00:05:23,708 --> 00:05:26,000
with a really weird name I
can't remember at the moment.

106
00:05:26,083 --> 00:05:27,458
Anthem works in a similar way.

107
00:05:27,541 --> 00:05:29,500
It rewrites genetic code, right?

108
00:05:29,583 --> 00:05:30,833
--[DEANA] Huh?!
--[DOCTORS gasp]

109
00:05:33,583 --> 00:05:35,125
[DEANA]
U-Uh... Uh...

110
00:05:35,208 --> 00:05:36,541
[KIRILL]
During normal gene editing,


111
00:05:36,625 --> 00:05:38,666
there's always a small chance
that an error can occur.


112
00:05:38,750 --> 00:05:41,166
A mutation, which can
awaken dormant genes.


113
00:05:41,250 --> 00:05:44,041
What we refer to as "Overdrive,"
is really just that.

114
00:05:44,125 --> 00:05:46,958
It occurs as a result of
these errors in the code.

115
00:05:47,041 --> 00:05:49,041
I would imagine that Anthem
is kind of similar

116
00:05:49,125 --> 00:05:51,166
to a bacteria molecule
in that way,

117
00:05:51,250 --> 00:05:55,625
'cause I think bacteria contain
something called a vector.

118
00:05:55,708 --> 00:05:57,208
Yeah, that does sound right.

119
00:05:57,291 --> 00:06:00,250
Vectors copy genetic material
and deliver it to other cells.

120
00:06:00,333 --> 00:06:01,500
Right!

121
00:06:01,583 --> 00:06:03,375
They really just behave
as carriers in that way.

122
00:06:03,458 --> 00:06:06,583
It's rare, but this process
can cause the genes to mutate.

123
00:06:06,666 --> 00:06:10,958
And the mutations can affect
the physical body, as well.

124
00:06:11,041 --> 00:06:12,333
Am I in the ballpark?

125
00:06:12,416 --> 00:06:13,833
Yeah, you're basically right.

126
00:06:13,916 --> 00:06:15,791
[sputtering]

127
00:06:15,875 --> 00:06:17,250
[DOCTOR HOPE]
Wonderful work!

128
00:06:17,333 --> 00:06:19,541
I've always dreamed of
meeting an investigator

129
00:06:19,625 --> 00:06:21,208
who really knows his stuff!

130
00:06:21,291 --> 00:06:22,750
[KAY]
Huh?!

131
00:06:22,833 --> 00:06:24,958
If it's not too much to ask,
could you do me a little favor?

132
00:06:25,041 --> 00:06:28,000
Can SEVEN-O's leadership put me
in contact with the military?

133
00:06:28,083 --> 00:06:28,625
[gasps]

134
00:06:28,708 --> 00:06:29,875
Dr. Hope means it.

135
00:06:29,958 --> 00:06:31,958
He's appealed to the
military many times

136
00:06:32,041 --> 00:06:34,250
to start clinical trials
for medical Anthem.

137
00:06:34,333 --> 00:06:37,208
I'm... not sure
how to respond. Uh--

138
00:06:37,291 --> 00:06:40,333
Hey. Who the hell are you?

139
00:06:43,583 --> 00:06:46,083
[JEFFREY]
Pardon me.

140
00:06:46,166 --> 00:06:47,250
Excuse me, sir?

141
00:06:47,333 --> 00:06:49,791
Would you be so kind
as to help me?

142
00:06:51,333 --> 00:06:53,458
This means a lot to me.
Thank you.

143
00:06:53,541 --> 00:06:55,125
It's nothing.

144
00:06:55,208 --> 00:06:57,541
[GUS]
Ladies! Can I ask you somethin'?

145
00:06:57,625 --> 00:06:59,291
Do both of you have boyfriends?

146
00:06:59,375 --> 00:07:00,916
[FEMALE 10A] That's none
of your business, kid.

147
00:07:01,000 --> 00:07:02,000
[JEFFREY]
Poor guy...

148
00:07:02,083 --> 00:07:03,791
Goin' after every girl
he sees lately.

149
00:07:03,875 --> 00:07:05,250
Guess he's just at that age.

150
00:07:05,333 --> 00:07:06,625
Does it worry you?

151
00:07:06,708 --> 00:07:10,083
No, not at all.
Makes me happy.

152
00:07:10,166 --> 00:07:12,666
That boy spends all
of his time with me.

153
00:07:12,750 --> 00:07:14,041
It's gonna be hard.

154
00:07:14,125 --> 00:07:16,666
He has a lot of suffering in
store for him when I go.

155
00:07:16,750 --> 00:07:19,916
So, I like to see him let
loose, like a normal kid.

156
00:07:20,000 --> 00:07:21,375
[laughing]

157
00:07:21,458 --> 00:07:23,583
[PATIENT 10A coughing]

158
00:07:23,666 --> 00:07:25,583
[PATIENT 10A]
Please... help me...

159
00:07:25,666 --> 00:07:28,166
I'm not ready to die yet.

160
00:07:29,208 --> 00:07:31,000
[APPLE]
That idiot? You're kidding me.

161
00:07:31,083 --> 00:07:32,416
[DEANA]
No, I'm serious!

162
00:07:32,500 --> 00:07:35,250
He started talking like a
totally different person.

163
00:07:35,333 --> 00:07:36,750
Kay was there!

164
00:07:36,833 --> 00:07:38,333
[KAY] It really seemed like
he turned into someone else!

165
00:07:38,416 --> 00:07:41,041
[APPLE] Did he get into some
kind of weird drug or something?

166
00:07:41,125 --> 00:07:42,666
[KIRILL]
Hey! I'm right here, you know!

167
00:07:42,750 --> 00:07:44,416
Look, it doesn't
make any sense!

168
00:07:44,500 --> 00:07:46,708
You're dumb, so how were you
spouting that mumbo-jumbo

169
00:07:46,791 --> 00:07:48,083
about Anthem and
genes and stuff!

170
00:07:48,166 --> 00:07:49,500
Well, if you must know...

171
00:07:49,583 --> 00:07:50,958
[DOUG]
See, the thing about Anthem is

172
00:07:51,041 --> 00:07:52,833
that it alters the human genome.

173
00:07:52,916 --> 00:07:54,708
Sometimes it induces
rapid evolution,

174
00:07:54,791 --> 00:07:56,291
which we call Overdrive.

175
00:07:56,375 --> 00:07:59,416
The drug eliminates all your
natural, genetic limiters.

176
00:07:59,500 --> 00:08:01,375
I mean, he gave me all
the basic information,

177
00:08:01,458 --> 00:08:02,791
I just filled in the
blanks, you know?

178
00:08:02,875 --> 00:08:04,666
Okay, I'm officially pissed off.

179
00:08:04,750 --> 00:08:06,041
Told you.

180
00:08:06,125 --> 00:08:07,541
[KIRILL] Why don't you guys
stop stuffing your faces

181
00:08:07,625 --> 00:08:09,000
and do some work?

182
00:08:09,083 --> 00:08:11,041
Are you putting something
together for this new case?

183
00:08:11,125 --> 00:08:13,750
They just asked for
my help is all.

184
00:08:13,833 --> 00:08:15,500
Figured I'd slap
something together.

185
00:08:15,583 --> 00:08:17,458
I'm handing it in
to Travis in a bit.

186
00:08:17,541 --> 00:08:19,875
Well, then, I'm happy
to lend a hand with that.

187
00:08:19,958 --> 00:08:22,083
Since you only have a
rudimentary grasp of such

188
00:08:22,166 --> 00:08:24,291
subjects, you should have an
expert eye checking your work.

189
00:08:24,375 --> 00:08:25,583
I'll be fine, thanks.

190
00:08:25,666 --> 00:08:28,291
You're an amateur--
you can't possibly do it.

191
00:08:29,041 --> 00:08:32,791
[APPLE] Huh? Although, you're
wise to choose that paper.

192
00:08:32,875 --> 00:08:34,041
[KIRILL]
Huh...?

193
00:08:34,125 --> 00:08:35,208
That paper, there.

194
00:08:35,291 --> 00:08:37,291
"On the Potentialities
of Silent Genes."

195
00:08:37,375 --> 00:08:39,375
It was published when
I was just a kid.

196
00:08:39,458 --> 00:08:43,208
I read it when I was 12 or
13--fascinating stuff.

197
00:08:43,291 --> 00:08:44,583
I'm glad you like my work.

198
00:08:44,666 --> 00:08:45,708
[ALL gasp]

199
00:08:45,791 --> 00:08:47,250
You mean you wrote it?!

200
00:08:47,333 --> 00:08:48,583
Inconceivable!

201
00:08:48,666 --> 00:08:51,083
I had to do something to
pay my way through school!

202
00:08:51,166 --> 00:08:52,458
Although, it's been
so many years

203
00:08:52,541 --> 00:08:54,916
since it was published,
I've forgotten it all.

204
00:08:55,000 --> 00:08:57,833
[KAY] Who abandons a career
in genetics to become a cop?

205
00:08:57,916 --> 00:08:59,333
[KIRILL]
It's not like that.

206
00:08:59,416 --> 00:09:01,208
I read about it in a manga
and thought it was kinda cool.

207
00:09:01,291 --> 00:09:02,375
So, I studied up.

208
00:09:02,458 --> 00:09:03,583
[STUDENT 10A]
Kirill, you're crazy, man!

209
00:09:03,666 --> 00:09:05,583
"Kinda cool"...?

210
00:09:05,666 --> 00:09:07,625
Kirill has been a genius
this entire time?

211
00:09:07,708 --> 00:09:10,291
Stop, I am by no means
a genius, come on.

212
00:09:10,375 --> 00:09:12,041
I just busted my hump
on that one paper

213
00:09:12,125 --> 00:09:14,166
to try and score some
sweet scholarship money.

214
00:09:14,250 --> 00:09:15,541
The minute that dough paid out,

215
00:09:15,625 --> 00:09:17,333
I forgot every word
I had written!

216
00:09:17,416 --> 00:09:20,333
[DEANA] I reject this! I won't
entertain the possibility

217
00:09:20,416 --> 00:09:21,916
that you're not a moron!

218
00:09:22,000 --> 00:09:24,791
It's gonna take me quite some
time to adjust to the idea, too.

219
00:09:24,875 --> 00:09:26,541
Then keep telling yourself
whatever you need

220
00:09:26,625 --> 00:09:29,708
to feel better. Oh, question.
I can't seem to figure out

221
00:09:29,791 --> 00:09:32,333
exactly what they put
in the anti-AMS bullets.

222
00:09:32,416 --> 00:09:33,583
Any leads there?

223
00:09:33,666 --> 00:09:34,666
I dunno.

224
00:09:34,750 --> 00:09:36,875
That's highly classified
military intel.

225
00:09:36,958 --> 00:09:39,000
Ah, well, that's a bummer.

226
00:09:39,083 --> 00:09:42,041
Hey, are these the only other
papers we have access to?

227
00:09:42,125 --> 00:09:44,916
Kirill, wait a sec.
Yuri's still in there.

228
00:09:45,000 --> 00:09:46,125
[KIRILL gasps]

229
00:09:46,208 --> 00:09:47,541
[APPLE] She's undergoing
routine maintenance.

230
00:09:47,625 --> 00:09:49,125
Should be wrapping up
any minute now.

231
00:09:49,208 --> 00:09:50,625
What? Maintenance? Come on,

232
00:09:50,708 --> 00:09:52,833
it's not like she's a real
robot or anything like that!

233
00:09:52,916 --> 00:09:56,333
Whoa. So, she's, like, totally
naked in there right now?

234
00:09:56,416 --> 00:09:58,125
It's prob'ly best
you don't look.

235
00:09:58,208 --> 00:10:00,458
It's nothing like what you
might imagine, I promise.

236
00:10:00,541 --> 00:10:02,000
[door creaking]

237
00:10:07,166 --> 00:10:07,875
[gasps]

238
00:10:07,958 --> 00:10:09,250
[ALL gasp]

239
00:10:09,333 --> 00:10:10,958
Were you spying on your
naked subordinate in there?

240
00:10:11,041 --> 00:10:12,250
What? No, no, no!

241
00:10:12,333 --> 00:10:14,125
Oh, did the sight
get you so riled up

242
00:10:14,208 --> 00:10:16,250
you spilled your coffee?

243
00:10:16,333 --> 00:10:18,958
Just forget the whole
thing, all right?

244
00:10:19,041 --> 00:10:21,500
You! Have you finished
those damn reports yet?

245
00:10:21,583 --> 00:10:22,833
Huh?!

246
00:10:23,875 --> 00:10:26,041
[KIRILL]
Jeez! Crap!

247
00:10:31,541 --> 00:10:32,750
[DOUG]
Huh?

248
00:10:33,875 --> 00:10:36,416
[KIRILL]
Uh. What the--?!

249
00:10:36,500 --> 00:10:37,500
[GUS yelps]

250
00:10:37,583 --> 00:10:39,541
Hey, Hold on!

251
00:10:39,625 --> 00:10:41,291
Wait a sec!

252
00:10:41,375 --> 00:10:43,333
Let me go!
You big, dumb loser!

253
00:10:43,416 --> 00:10:44,666
Don't sleep here.

254
00:10:44,750 --> 00:10:46,958
It's super dangerous--
why don't you go on home?

255
00:10:47,041 --> 00:10:49,250
[GUS] 'Cause I don't
have a home, okay?

256
00:10:49,333 --> 00:10:51,625
Can't you just leave
me alone, man?

257
00:10:51,708 --> 00:10:54,500
I'm not a damn criminal!
Go away!

258
00:10:54,583 --> 00:10:57,125
You like this?
Renoir is awesome.

259
00:10:57,208 --> 00:10:58,041
Uh?

260
00:10:58,125 --> 00:11:00,291
I can't die yet.

261
00:11:00,375 --> 00:11:02,166
He still needs me.

262
00:11:02,250 --> 00:11:04,125
I can't leave him.

263
00:11:04,875 --> 00:11:06,000
[JEFFREY gasps]

264
00:11:15,958 --> 00:11:18,000
--[LANDLADY] Oh, I see.
--Huh?

265
00:11:18,083 --> 00:11:19,541
[LANDLADY] I thought
you might swing that way,

266
00:11:19,625 --> 00:11:21,208
but don't you think
he's kinda young?

267
00:11:21,291 --> 00:11:22,250
Ew, gross!

268
00:11:22,333 --> 00:11:24,500
Oh god, no!
What's wrong with you?!

269
00:11:24,583 --> 00:11:26,333
Don't even joke
about that stuff, gah!

270
00:11:26,416 --> 00:11:28,333
[LANDLADY]
Whatever, you have guests!

271
00:11:28,416 --> 00:11:30,333
We brought the Derick's
Special you ordered!

272
00:11:30,416 --> 00:11:32,333
We came all the way out
here to hand deliver it!

273
00:11:32,416 --> 00:11:34,083
Wait, Derick's here, too?

274
00:11:34,166 --> 00:11:35,333
But, why?

275
00:11:35,416 --> 00:11:37,000
He wouldn't let me come alone.

276
00:11:37,083 --> 00:11:39,291
Said women should always
have an escort at night.

277
00:11:39,375 --> 00:11:40,458
[POCHI meows]

278
00:11:40,541 --> 00:11:41,916
[GUS]
We got evicted.

279
00:11:42,000 --> 00:11:43,958
They kicked us out
for missing rent.

280
00:11:44,041 --> 00:11:45,166
Does your dad know?

281
00:11:45,250 --> 00:11:46,666
That you don't have
the money to pay it?

282
00:11:46,750 --> 00:11:48,375
Well, I had the money.

283
00:11:48,458 --> 00:11:49,958
He set up an account
for me to pay rent

284
00:11:50,041 --> 00:11:52,333
and other things that I need.

285
00:11:52,416 --> 00:11:53,625
But that's all gone now.

286
00:11:53,708 --> 00:11:55,166
I had to use it
for his treatments.

287
00:11:55,250 --> 00:11:57,625
Yet you're still flashing
wads of cash to pick up girls.

288
00:11:57,708 --> 00:12:01,083
No, what was-- I wanted...

289
00:12:01,916 --> 00:12:03,041
Uh.

290
00:12:03,125 --> 00:12:06,458
On the day I was born,
my mom passed away.

291
00:12:06,541 --> 00:12:10,000
After she died, Dad just
worked and took care of me.

292
00:12:10,083 --> 00:12:12,333
He never did anything
to have fun or let loose.

293
00:12:12,416 --> 00:12:13,916
[DERICK whimpers]

294
00:12:14,000 --> 00:12:15,541
[GUS]
So, I was doing it for him.

295
00:12:15,625 --> 00:12:18,625
I wanted him to spend time with
a pretty girl before he died.

296
00:12:18,708 --> 00:12:21,833
Otherwise his life would
seem so empty and sad.

297
00:12:21,916 --> 00:12:25,916
And if that was the case, I
could never live with the guilt.

298
00:12:26,000 --> 00:12:28,625
So you did all that
stuff for your dad?

299
00:12:28,708 --> 00:12:29,916
[LANDLADY]
Come on, big guy,

300
00:12:30,000 --> 00:12:32,875
why don't you lend me
a hand in the kitchen?

301
00:12:32,958 --> 00:12:34,750
The least I can do
for that poor kid

302
00:12:34,833 --> 00:12:38,208
is offer him a nice pot
of after-dinner tea.

303
00:12:38,291 --> 00:12:39,458
What is it?

304
00:12:39,541 --> 00:12:41,333
[KIRILL] You don't get
to make that call, kid!

305
00:12:41,416 --> 00:12:42,583
You can't decide

306
00:12:42,666 --> 00:12:44,583
whether your dad's life
was worthwhile or not!

307
00:12:44,666 --> 00:12:46,083
How do you think
he'd feel if he knew

308
00:12:46,166 --> 00:12:47,583
that's what his own
son thought of him?

309
00:12:47,666 --> 00:12:49,791
That'd be even more painful!

310
00:12:49,875 --> 00:12:51,125
Kirill...

311
00:12:51,208 --> 00:12:53,166
Who cares if you've got
money, or girls like you,

312
00:12:53,250 --> 00:12:55,958
or you've got an easy
life. He's got you.

313
00:12:56,041 --> 00:12:57,833
Sure, life is smoother
with that stuff.

314
00:12:57,916 --> 00:13:00,458
But, still, that's not
what's important!

315
00:13:00,541 --> 00:13:02,125
Even if he has to leave you.

316
00:13:02,208 --> 00:13:04,333
Knowing his son's alive
and well because of him?

317
00:13:04,416 --> 00:13:07,500
That is a life well-lived!

318
00:13:07,583 --> 00:13:09,125
So, you have reason to smile,

319
00:13:09,208 --> 00:13:11,416
and celebrate your dad's
life for what it is.

320
00:13:11,500 --> 00:13:15,000
You owe it to him to take care
of yourself and be happy.

321
00:13:15,083 --> 00:13:16,125
What the--?

322
00:13:16,208 --> 00:13:17,583
[snores]

323
00:13:17,666 --> 00:13:19,958
Guess my lecture
put him to sleep.

324
00:13:21,166 --> 00:13:23,125
[MILLA]
You must have been so lonely.

325
00:13:23,208 --> 00:13:25,125
After Grandpa died.

326
00:13:26,083 --> 00:13:29,166
I'm sorry... for leaving
you alone so long.

327
00:13:29,250 --> 00:13:30,791
I already forgave you.

328
00:13:30,875 --> 00:13:33,458
I'm glad we're together now.

329
00:13:33,541 --> 00:13:35,541
[phone rings]

330
00:13:35,625 --> 00:13:37,416
Yeah? Kirill speaking.

331
00:13:37,500 --> 00:13:40,333
Huh? How did that happen?

332
00:13:40,416 --> 00:13:42,666
Fine, whatever, I'm on my way.

333
00:13:42,750 --> 00:13:43,666
Listen.

334
00:13:43,750 --> 00:13:45,583
Think you could look after him?

335
00:13:49,375 --> 00:13:50,500
Yo.

336
00:13:51,208 --> 00:13:52,541
What the hell, man?

337
00:13:52,625 --> 00:13:54,625
Idiot! Why would you
leave the hospital?

338
00:13:54,708 --> 00:13:56,375
Don't you ever
wanna get better?!

339
00:13:56,458 --> 00:13:57,958
You bring the forensics kit?

340
00:13:58,041 --> 00:13:59,625
Don't ignore my reprimand!

341
00:13:59,708 --> 00:14:01,750
[DOUG]
That guy--he's in Overdrive.

342
00:14:01,833 --> 00:14:04,208
Why do I even bother with you?

343
00:14:06,333 --> 00:14:08,833
[KIRILL] Which guy?
The baldy with the sandwich?

344
00:14:10,833 --> 00:14:13,291
What? My scanner's not working.

345
00:14:13,375 --> 00:14:14,500
So that's it.

346
00:14:14,583 --> 00:14:16,791
Will you stop being
so cryptic and explain?

347
00:14:16,875 --> 00:14:19,416
Damn! Dude, wait up!

348
00:14:19,500 --> 00:14:21,666
[DOUG] That same guy was
knocking on death's door

349
00:14:21,750 --> 00:14:24,416
in the hospital this afternoon.

350
00:14:24,500 --> 00:14:26,291
The girls are on
this case, right.

351
00:14:26,375 --> 00:14:28,291
[DOUG gasps]

352
00:14:28,375 --> 00:14:30,333
[KIRILL] Several patients have
checked out of that hospital

353
00:14:30,416 --> 00:14:31,833
on their own only to end up dead

354
00:14:31,916 --> 00:14:33,875
not long after from
Anthem overdose.

355
00:14:33,958 --> 00:14:36,250
This has got to be related.

356
00:14:39,666 --> 00:14:40,666
[DOUG gasps]

357
00:14:42,333 --> 00:14:44,583
You. I saw you at the hospital.

358
00:14:44,666 --> 00:14:46,708
[gasps] Drop the knife,
let's talk!

359
00:14:46,791 --> 00:14:48,583
[PATIENT 10A] There's nothing
for us to talk about.

360
00:14:48,666 --> 00:14:50,500
[KIRILL] I'm warning you!
Drop it, or I'll shoot!

361
00:14:50,583 --> 00:14:52,375
I needed the light of hope!

362
00:14:52,458 --> 00:14:55,750
And I found it in that hospital.
But I need more, dammit!

363
00:14:55,833 --> 00:14:57,166
[gunshot]

364
00:14:57,250 --> 00:14:58,458
[gasps]

365
00:15:01,375 --> 00:15:04,250
Just stay still.
You need a doctor.

366
00:15:06,000 --> 00:15:08,916
Look, I only ever did
what they told me to!

367
00:15:09,000 --> 00:15:10,500
[KIRILL]
Wait!

368
00:15:10,583 --> 00:15:11,791
Shit!

369
00:15:13,125 --> 00:15:15,166
Now, let me see the kit.

370
00:15:15,250 --> 00:15:16,916
[DOCTOR HOPE]
He declined treatment.

371
00:15:17,000 --> 00:15:20,291
Said he was finished and left.
Walked out without a word.

372
00:15:20,375 --> 00:15:22,000
[KIRILL] But, then,
there was another patient

373
00:15:22,083 --> 00:15:22,875
at this hospital who--

374
00:15:22,958 --> 00:15:24,750
Correction, a former patient.

375
00:15:24,833 --> 00:15:25,875
Pardon me, Doctor.

376
00:15:25,958 --> 00:15:27,333
May I ask your opinion,

377
00:15:27,416 --> 00:15:29,583
you being an esteemed
medical professional?

378
00:15:29,666 --> 00:15:30,708
Yes, what is it?

379
00:15:30,791 --> 00:15:32,875
We found Anthem in
the patient's blood.

380
00:15:32,958 --> 00:15:35,875
Do you have any idea how
that might have happened?

381
00:15:35,958 --> 00:15:38,250
He fled the scene in spite
of some nasty wounds,

382
00:15:38,333 --> 00:15:39,708
not to mention his illness.

383
00:15:39,791 --> 00:15:41,916
It seems clear that his body
has undergone some sort of

384
00:15:42,000 --> 00:15:45,125
physical change, yet our systems
didn't detect Overdrive.

385
00:15:45,208 --> 00:15:47,708
I'm just wondering what you
make of that, Doctor.

386
00:15:47,791 --> 00:15:50,458
There's not enough information
to make anything of it.

387
00:15:50,541 --> 00:15:53,291
Although... When you're at
death's door and you feel like

388
00:15:53,375 --> 00:15:56,291
a shell of your former self,
don't you think it's normal

389
00:15:56,375 --> 00:15:58,916
to seek relief in whatever
form you can find it?

390
00:15:59,000 --> 00:16:01,458
Yes, but... Anthem?

391
00:16:01,541 --> 00:16:03,250
[DOCTOR HOPE]
Now please leave.

392
00:16:04,458 --> 00:16:06,708
[DOUG] We should talk with
Travis about this tomorrow,

393
00:16:06,791 --> 00:16:09,791
probably not enough
for a warrant, though.

394
00:16:09,875 --> 00:16:14,125
And I'll fill out those
reports. Eventually.

395
00:16:14,208 --> 00:16:15,458
If Anthem had been developed

396
00:16:15,541 --> 00:16:17,833
for medicinal use from
the very beginning,

397
00:16:17,916 --> 00:16:19,583
do you think things
would be different?

398
00:16:19,666 --> 00:16:20,291
Better, even?

399
00:16:20,375 --> 00:16:21,875
Rich men make that call.

400
00:16:21,958 --> 00:16:24,541
Whether a drug is
poison or a cure.

401
00:16:24,625 --> 00:16:28,166
I think it's up to those
who use it, in the end.

402
00:16:30,375 --> 00:16:31,625
[KIRILL yelps]

403
00:16:31,708 --> 00:16:33,875
You have to tell me what's
happening to my body!

404
00:16:33,958 --> 00:16:35,916
I'm bleeding, but it
doesn't even hurt!

405
00:16:36,000 --> 00:16:39,041
My senses are failing--
I can't taste or smell.


406
00:16:39,125 --> 00:16:40,125
Help me!


407
00:16:40,208 --> 00:16:41,583
I'm still getting
an error message!

408
00:16:41,666 --> 00:16:43,458
I can't feel heat or
cold or anything!

409
00:16:43,541 --> 00:16:45,833
Please! Tell me what's
happening to me!

410
00:16:45,916 --> 00:16:47,708
If you'll take me to the
person who offered you

411
00:16:47,791 --> 00:16:49,958
the light of hope,
we can help you.

412
00:16:50,041 --> 00:16:52,166
We'll find the answers you seek.

413
00:16:53,375 --> 00:16:55,875
Derick? Where's Gus?

414
00:16:56,750 --> 00:16:59,166
[GUS]
Dad, it's me! Huh? Huh?!

415
00:16:59,250 --> 00:17:00,875
He can't be--!

416
00:17:03,041 --> 00:17:05,041
[PATIENT 10A] I just want
to feel something again!

417
00:17:05,125 --> 00:17:05,958
[KIRILL]
He's fast!

418
00:17:06,041 --> 00:17:07,666
There is nothing
for you to fear.

419
00:17:07,750 --> 00:17:10,875
If you take this medicine,
you will find the light of hope.

420
00:17:10,958 --> 00:17:14,125
Isn't there a 30% chance
that takin' it'll kill me?

421
00:17:14,208 --> 00:17:16,875
And the side effects--
aren't they substantial?

422
00:17:16,958 --> 00:17:18,750
[DOCTOR HOPE]
We'll monitor you for 24 hours

423
00:17:18,833 --> 00:17:20,541
and hopefully none
of that will happen.

424
00:17:20,625 --> 00:17:22,500
If you can just make it
through the initial phase,

425
00:17:22,583 --> 00:17:23,833
you'll be free.

426
00:17:23,916 --> 00:17:25,791
Look, Jeffrey. At this rate,

427
00:17:25,875 --> 00:17:28,583
you've only got ten days left
to live, if even that long.

428
00:17:28,666 --> 00:17:29,500
[JEFFREY gasping]

429
00:17:29,583 --> 00:17:31,125
Is that true?

430
00:17:34,041 --> 00:17:36,458
The decision is yours alone.

431
00:17:37,166 --> 00:17:38,375
[JEFFREY gasping]

432
00:17:38,458 --> 00:17:40,541
[footsteps]

433
00:17:40,625 --> 00:17:41,750
[PATIENT 10A grunts]

434
00:17:41,833 --> 00:17:43,125
[JEFFREY gasps]

435
00:17:43,208 --> 00:17:44,375
What's happening to me?

436
00:17:44,458 --> 00:17:45,416
My body is failing!

437
00:17:45,500 --> 00:17:46,416
The loser's here?

438
00:17:46,500 --> 00:17:47,291
Whoa, Gus?

439
00:17:47,375 --> 00:17:48,333
[PATIENT 10A]
Doctor!

440
00:17:48,416 --> 00:17:49,791
Now just relax.

441
00:17:49,875 --> 00:17:51,791
This medicine will
make you feel better.

442
00:17:51,875 --> 00:17:54,333
I asked you a question, dammit!

443
00:17:55,541 --> 00:17:56,666
What the--? Whoa.

444
00:17:56,750 --> 00:18:00,208
[PATIENTS groaning]

445
00:18:00,291 --> 00:18:03,458
[DOUG] Their influence spreads
even further than I thought.

446
00:18:04,791 --> 00:18:06,083
[KIRILL]
Esperanza?!

447
00:18:06,166 --> 00:18:08,041
Their goal must be to figure
out the proper ratios

448
00:18:08,125 --> 00:18:10,291
for the anti-AMS bullets.

449
00:18:11,083 --> 00:18:12,625
[DOUG] They're injecting
patients with Anthem,

450
00:18:12,708 --> 00:18:14,333
then injecting them with
the drugs in the bullets

451
00:18:14,416 --> 00:18:16,625
in different proportions
to find out what works.

452
00:18:16,708 --> 00:18:18,375
They're using
these men as lab rats.

453
00:18:18,458 --> 00:18:20,291
Then those error messages
I was getting...

454
00:18:20,375 --> 00:18:23,291
They must be a result of
the drugs partially working.

455
00:18:23,375 --> 00:18:26,166
Each one of those five drugs
is deadly on its own.

456
00:18:26,250 --> 00:18:28,916
The patient's good
for data, but then...

457
00:18:29,000 --> 00:18:31,041
It's a necessary sacrifice!

458
00:18:31,125 --> 00:18:33,916
If we can attain the benefits of
Anthem without the risks, then,

459
00:18:34,000 --> 00:18:35,458
think of the medical potential!

460
00:18:35,541 --> 00:18:36,666
[PATIENT 10A]
Give me more Anthem, now!

461
00:18:36,750 --> 00:18:39,250
[DOCTOR HOPE]
What are you doing? Stop!

462
00:18:39,333 --> 00:18:41,375
[PATIENT 10A]
I'll test the medical potential!

463
00:18:41,458 --> 00:18:43,458
--[KIRILL gasps]
--No, don't!

464
00:18:47,041 --> 00:18:49,833
Vitality!

465
00:18:57,125 --> 00:18:58,333
Vitality this!

466
00:18:58,416 --> 00:19:02,750
[PATIENT 10A groans]
It hurts.

467
00:19:02,833 --> 00:19:05,125
You have to save me!

468
00:19:06,250 --> 00:19:09,958
Please save me. It... hurts...

469
00:19:10,041 --> 00:19:12,166
[DOCTOR HOPE] He's nothing
more than an animated corpse

470
00:19:12,250 --> 00:19:15,208
awaiting death. And you are
to blame for his suffering!

471
00:19:15,291 --> 00:19:17,833
Your coming here shortened his
life and drove him to the edge!

472
00:19:17,916 --> 00:19:21,916
Save me. I don't want to die.

473
00:19:22,000 --> 00:19:24,666
I'm giving my patients hope
in the face of imminent doom!

474
00:19:24,750 --> 00:19:26,958
[KIRILL] Don't you dare talk
about hope! Shut your mouth!

475
00:19:27,041 --> 00:19:28,541
Enough, let him go.

476
00:19:28,625 --> 00:19:30,875
Jeffery. Do you want to live?

477
00:19:30,958 --> 00:19:31,750
[gasps]

478
00:19:31,833 --> 00:19:34,208
Yes? Then you have to help me!

479
00:19:34,291 --> 00:19:36,250
Use the Anthem, now!

480
00:19:36,333 --> 00:19:39,416
If you take the drug, you'll
have the strength of a giant!

481
00:19:39,500 --> 00:19:41,625
And the vitality to
beat your illness!

482
00:19:41,708 --> 00:19:42,708
[KIRILL]
You liar!

483
00:19:42,791 --> 00:19:44,541
[DOCTOR HOPE]
Come, let's run away.

484
00:19:44,625 --> 00:19:47,958
I'm the only person in the
world who can keep you alive.

485
00:19:49,750 --> 00:19:51,666
[DOCTOR HOPE] Don't you
want to see him grow up?

486
00:19:51,750 --> 00:19:55,250
To see your son get married?
Meet your future grandkids?

487
00:19:57,041 --> 00:19:58,416
I do.

488
00:19:58,500 --> 00:19:59,458
Dad, stop it.

489
00:19:59,541 --> 00:20:00,291
Use it!

490
00:20:00,375 --> 00:20:01,916
No! Don't!

491
00:20:16,125 --> 00:20:17,583
[yells]

492
00:20:17,666 --> 00:20:18,916
[DOCTOR HOPE gasps]

493
00:20:19,000 --> 00:20:20,583
I refuse.

494
00:20:20,666 --> 00:20:23,625
You'll never make me a monster.

495
00:20:23,708 --> 00:20:26,875
I'd rather die as
my son's father.

496
00:20:36,625 --> 00:20:37,791
[DOUG]
Hello, Jeffrey.

497
00:20:37,875 --> 00:20:38,625
How are you doing?

498
00:20:38,708 --> 00:20:40,416
Much better, thanks.

499
00:20:40,500 --> 00:20:42,666
